David,

In your prior email you stated that your tests &quot;lean more towards being 
functional tests.&quot;  So I&#39;m curious as to why you don&#39;t think the 
following is adequately addressed by JFunc?

import junit.framework.*;
import junit.extensions.jfunc.*;

public class MultiFailureTest extends TestCase {

	public MultiFailureTest(String name) {
		super(name);
	}
	public void testMultipleFailures() {
	// use JFuncTestCase, which looks just like JUnit&#39;s TestCase, except it
	// uses it&#39;s own assert class that is non-static
	JFuncTestCase test = new JFuncTestCase(&quot;multi failure&quot;) {
		protected void runTest() {
			fail(&quot;one&quot;);
			fail(&quot;two&quot;);
		}
	};
	TestResult result = new TestResult();
	test.setFatal(false);  // make assertions non-fatal, hence allow 
for multiple failures
	test.run(result);
	assertEquals(&quot;number of failures&quot;,2,result.failureCount());
	}
}

If this feature is useful for unit testing, then by all means put it in 
JUnit.  If it&#39;s not or questionable, put it in JFunc.

-shane

http://jfunc.sourceforge.net

